<font color="#FF0000">OUR TEACHERS, OURSELVES.</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug 20 20:52:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
To John &amp; Gerald, both of you remind me of a supervisor who had just gotten his Sgt. stripes when I was on the police department. We had all attended some new sensitive classes on how to deal with crises, through dialog.<br>
One day an &quot;Officer needs Help,&quot; call came out.<br>
Much like the recent UPS strike, garment factory employees most of whom were Spanish speaking were striking and the situation had heated up to a boiling point. <br>
When I arrived, people were screaming and shouting at each other and it was evident that the officers in charge were not going to be able to disfuse the situation. <br>
The danger was that we were all inside the building with numerous, knives, scissors and other potential dangerous weapons within easy reach of the employees on strike as well as by management personal. <br>
The officers had already drawn their baton and within seconds, it was going to be a free for all.<br>
I jumped up on a table and shouted to everyone in Spanish. This caught everyone by surprise, as most of the shouting and screaming inside had been done in English. The officers present didn't know what I was shouting, but the recognized me and the uniform I wore. <br>
I issued orders for every employee without further comment from them to get out of the building and for management to shut up and to get into their offices. I did this in Spanish and surprising everyone did that without further comment. Within a few minutes the only ones left inside the main factory were the officers.<br>
Once they were separated the labor negotiation team from our department was called and while they were enroute that new supervisor came up to me and said,<br>
&quot;Hey, this is a good chance for us to practice that crisis negotiation ideas we had been though. Why, don't we go back inside and call them all together and try that.&quot;<br>
Without a word to him, I go on my bike and drove away. <br><br>
John you stated,  <br>
&quot;Would note that it's not absolutely necessary to dehumanize the enemy in warfare to get a great amount of carnage.&quot; <br>
While that is true, How much do we need to dehumanize an individual before we make the decision to kill them in war? I believe it is both necessary for some and unnecessary for others. A lot depends upon our own upbringing. What values our parents, society and others instilled upon us. <br>
When my young daughter first saw a sad movie, she turned to her mom and said, &quot;Mommy that makes my eyes water.&quot; What we don't understand often affect us in ways we can not find words to explain. <br>
That is where we need to start. Why are we so bothered by a word used by others, is it because of our own upbringing, our own hidden guilt? Is it because someone has though us that certain words are wrong is that what makes them wrong? Or is it because our own hearts are dark?<br>
Is it because we have been told that boys don't cry, that today we find it hard to say to a fellow vet, thanks, I love you. You meant a lot to me.  Izzie the Shoeshone Indian at the reunion when we departed would only say to me, &quot;You make my eyes water.&quot;<br>
Do we follow others because of their degrees? Their credentials, ranks or position? <br>
The only reason I obtained my master's degree was because I knew that those initials after my name would make it easlier for me to sell the books I've yet to write. <br>
Sagan manipulated many by writing about what he didn't believe but caused others to reconsider.<br>
I learned in High School that teachers weren't really very smart. It wasn't my english teacher that thought me to love reading and writing, it was my art teacher. The only thing I remember about my English teacher was that she had nice long legs, but I remember much about my art teacher who thought me to be all I can be. To make my own roads in life, to not be concerned about what others think about me if my motives are honest and right. <br><br>
In my first firefight, the first time I opened up in combat, I realized that I was not firing at the enemy because he was a communist, because he was a gook, because he was a north Vietnamese soldier and my enemy. <br><br>
From the book; Dreams of Glory, Clear fields of Fire.<br><br>
&quot;I realized that I had responded to Jones' firing, opened up without reservation and had shot at the enemy in retaliation. I had shot at the enemy who killed Bro and Stroker, wounded Turner and McGinley and had taken US government issued military weapons. I realized I had opened fire for Bro and not for the South Vietnamese people.&quot; (Copyright Cook Barela 1997)<br><br>
For awhile after that, I shot at the enemy because Marines were pinned down in their killing fields. It was nothing personal, just that I valued the life of those Marines more then the lives of the enemy shooting at them. But it wasn't long before I felt the heat of their personal aggression and determination to knock out my gun for the death and destruction I had reeked upon them. That I could not understand for the longest time.<br><br>
Now, I realize that on several occasions the enemy had made it personal, even at the expense of staying behind and sacrificing another soldier for that privilege. On at least three occasions they waited for me to get up from where they had pinned my gun down and opened fire in my direction only after I got up, although other Marines were already walking alongside of them or me. <br>
Why? Was it because of the death, pain and the sorrow I had inflicted upon their comrades? Were they then, firing at me for the same reasons I had first opened up in combat?<br><br>
Is that not what ART is in a sense referring to, when he wrote, <br>
&quot;I feel that at some dark level, the Vietnam War was really a conflict with ourselves, a throwback into our own struggle for independence from a &quot;master&quot;<br><br>
Who was our teacher? Who is our master?<br>

